\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 30}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}
{\xmlattrvalue 12}}}Half past twelve{\*\xmlclose}
 to half past one. Father would be in the house at a quarter to one prompt. It would take him a quarter of an hour to get home. And he would be out of the house at ten minutes past one. We always sat down at quarter-to-one prompt. At quarter to one di
nner was on the table had to be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 And tea time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Tea would be at quarter-to-six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What sort of a meal did you have then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 That used to vary. Bread and butter and jam mainly. Tea. And for an occasional treat, very rarely, I can remember po
tted meat, that you buy from the butchers; or some lettuce in season, tomatoes in season. But mostly bread and jam or bread }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid294071 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6504091\charrsid15301266  mar}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 garine when things were bad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What about on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 We had high tea on Sundays. That may be some boiled ham or a lit
tle bit of the cold meat and salad, and jelly and maybe a tin of fruit, or a tin of salmon, which was quite a luxury.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Then I suppose you'd have something at bedtime, a drink would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Not when we were children, no. Not until we started to work, then we were allowed a cup of cocoa and maybe a biscuit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Now you say your mother baked her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Was this on the three days when the oven was heated?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 The two days it was heated.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did she make cakes and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did she make her own jam or bottle fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. She wouldn't bottle fruit. She'd make marmalade and jam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would she preserve vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would she make pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes on one or two occasions she pickled some onions.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did she ever make wine or brew beer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. Herb beer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did she used to make up any medicines for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. Camomile tea and brimstone and treacle, castor oil of course was always a good standby, and malt extract, cod liver oil, sh
e used to mix up. She used to have various concoctions.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15301266  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Camomile tea Senna and linseed. She used to boil linseed and stick }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14093043\charrsid15301266 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 panish in it for coughs and colds in winter. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14093043\charrsid15301266 Spanich }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 \{ILLEGIBLE\}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14093043\charrsid15301266  liquorice}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you have a garden? Were you able to grow your own vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
My father took an allotment during the First World War and grew vegetables, before that they were all bought. This was the first time we grew any vegetables for the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would they buy fresh vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Sometimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Or would they be tinned or dried?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Mostly fresh vegetables. Not far out of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Astley
{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} you could go to what they called salad gardens and buy lettuces from people that grew them, on the outskirts of the village, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. You're soon in th
e country there. People used to grow things where they had a back garden and you used to go and buy them from the growers. Or in the winter you'd go to the greengrocer on the main road, and buy carrots and cabbages and cauliflowers and things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 When you did get your own allotment were you able to cope with all the needs of the family for fruit and vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh no. You'd buy in winter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did your parents keep any livestock for the family; hens, pigs, goats, etc.?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 In later years, yes, we 
had a few hens on the allotment. A little piece which was cut off with wire netting. I remember my father building a little hen cote and we'd probably have half a dozen hens there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Who looked after the hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 My father and mother and the two boys
; of course we were growing up then, in our teens, I was at any rate. I used to go and help feed the hens and clean the mess up. You know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you ever get some extra meat such as rabbit from poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Do you remember seeing your mother having less food to eat so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did your father have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. He was a heavy worker. Heavy industry. He had to. It was a necessary that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5570694\charrsid15301266 h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 e should be fed he was the breadwinner and had a very heavy rough job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 At the meal time were you allowed to talk during the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
No. It was a case of speak when you're spoken to. We weren't encouraged to talk. If we were asked questions we were supposed to give honest answers to them. I can't remember being 
invited to talk as a child except perhaps at parties when you were invited to give a recitation - something you learn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to eat a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh we had to have what was put on the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What was your parents' attitude if you every left anything uneaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Oh you got a lecture about it, you had to eat it, you weren't allowed to leave it. Waste not want not. These ideas were enforced. Nothing more 'till we'd eaten that. Oh yes we had to have what another gave us - or nothing or do without.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
If there was something on the table that you wanted. If you wanted the salt for instance, could you ask for it or did you have to wait for it to be passed round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
You would wait for it to be passed round. But if it was near you'd reach for it. Everybody helped themselves to what was on the table, in the way of ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Could you ask for a second helping of anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes but you didn't always get it. If you wanted a second helping you had to say well "}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12718837\charrsid15301266 There's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266  a bit of pudding left hands up who wants some more", and you shared it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a particular way and sit in a particular way at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Were you ever allowed to bring a book or bring toys up to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
When father got up. Mostly. Unless you had somewhere to to like. Errands to do or jobs to do and Mother would say well get up and do what 
I told you to do. Generally when father got up out of his chair, his easy chair, and got his pipe we got up from the table.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you have to ask if you could leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. Except when the meal was over and father got up. But if you wanted to leave before father got up you'd say 'May I leave the table?'.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 I suppose that all the family would sit at the table for the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you always all have the same places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Was it your mother who served the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How would she serve it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 She would give us all our portions served on the plates.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What order would she serve you in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Father first of course, and down from the eldest to the youngest, and herself last.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 When you had younger brothers and sisters where did they sit before they could feed themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 In a high chair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Who fed them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Mother and then the eldest sister. The teenage sister would help if she was there of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What age would the younger ones graduate to the stage of coming up to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 About four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Well now, can you tell me something about your mother, about the sort of woman she was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Very religious, both father and mother, attended church regularly. Father was a local preache
r in a way. He used to go about to various men's groups on Sunday afternoons - men's classes. Give them a talk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you feel you could talk easily to your mother about things. Could you confide in her?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No, we never volunteered it. Mother usuall
y got into our minds by questions. If she wanted to know what we were thinking we'd get questions. I can't think that we were encouraged to converse. We were taught to listen rather than talk. We would never volunteer to join in a conversation.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 If you had any special worry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 We used to keep it to ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You didn't confide either in your mother or your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 I don't think so. No. I can't remember opening my heart to anybody because we always felt, we always had a guilty conscience
 about things we used to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you confide in one another as children then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you feel close to your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did they show affection in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. My mother did, yes. I had a very good mother. But we were 
never spoiled. We were disciplined. There was very rigid discipline in the house. Mother would give us a religious talk in hour own fashion. This was bad - this was wrong and that was right and God wouldn't like us if we did this. Got this sort of religio
us atmosphere in the home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Certainly with respect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What above behaviour amongst the children? Were you brought up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh 
yes. But I can't say it always came off, you know. We used to quarrel. Have our little tiffs and quarrels and arguments over various possessions. We used to guard our rights as children. You don't play with my toys unless I know about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did your parents ever tell you you should hit back if another child hit you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 This was something we hadn't to do. It didn't always work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What sort of people do you think your parents hoped you would be when you grew up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 God fearing, respectable, law ab
iding citizens. Respect for the law and respect for your parents. We were taught the ten commandments and they were pretty well drilled into us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 And these were the main things that they considered to be important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What did they think about swearing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Oh Blasphemy. Absolutely taboo. We would be thrashed. Any wrong doing was reported to father when he came home and if we did anything really wrong we would get thrashed for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What sort of offences did you get punished for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Potty pilfering Swearing (but I don't think we'd ever dream of swearing). Potty pilfering in the houses I remember I got one of my thrashings for pinching my mother's pearl buttons. We used to play odd games with them in the street. We used t
o play one game with buttons - we used to set up a stone and put a pearl button on it and they'd throw a marble at it. And of course to get pearl buttons we used to have to take them out of the house. Then mother found half a dozen of her pearl buttons we
re missing and we got accused of it, we had to own up and that was a thrashing. Taking cake or biscuits without her knowledge, that was petty pilfering, and that was punishable as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Can you remember if there were minor offences that might be punished less severely than that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
No. I think that there were threats of a punishment or of being deprived of things. My parents would threaten that if that happens again we shan't take you to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Southport{\*\xmlclose}
 or something like that. They would threaten to deprive us of treats and threaten would be enough. Usually the threat would be quite sufficient to deter us from repeating minor offences.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 The thrashing was your father's job wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. What we call a deliberate punishment would be father. Mother would punish on impulse, you know, smacks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would you say that you received the ideas you had about now to behave from both your parents or ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 From both.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 One didn't play a more important part than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Well of course my mother
 saw most of us, father was away at work all day, and he was also in his own particular way a worker at the church and Sunday school and he was active in his trade union and temperance movement and the co-operative movement and we didn't quite see so much
 of him as we would see of my mother. I dare say my father would be out, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11957710\charrsid15301266 he\rquote d come home from work, had his tea and get warmed and probably }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 three nights a week, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11957710\charrsid15301266 he\rquote d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 \{ILLEGIBLE\}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11957710\charrsid15301266  somewhere}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266  to some sort of meeting which he considered important.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 When you had a birthday would that be any different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Not really, no. Maybe it would be remembered by just wishing 'Happy returns of the day', occasionally there might be a birthday cake. If it happened to be baking day she'd probably put a ca
ke in the oven and say this was a birthday cake. Perhaps put a bit of icing on top and a cherry and that would be a birthday cake. But I wouldn't say that happened all the time. My particular birthday was near Christmas and was generally forgotten. If I s
aid 'Where is my birthday cake, to my mother, she would say oh we're having your birthday cake on Christmas day. We're celebrating your birthday on Christmas Day. And that would have to suffice you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Was the same true of presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Well presen
ts were very, very rare indeed. I don't remember receiving any birthday presents of any consequence until I was twenty-one. When I was given a silver watch, and that was my first birthday present, that I remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you have guests in to celebrate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How would you spend Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Oh it was quite an exciting day, especially in the morning. We hung our stockings up as children, until about the age of ten, or eleven, possibly twelve, and we expected some sort of present. I think 
my twelfth birthday was celebrated by a very important present which was a 5/- Ingersoll watch, which was quite a gift in those days. That was my twelfth birthday and I was earning 2/- week as a paper roundsman and that was some sort of reward for this as
 I was contributing to the family income I got a present in the shape of at 5/- watch. This was something really good. Previous to that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12718837\charrsid15301266 Christmas}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266  presents would comprise of simple toys or games like Ludo or Dominoes, cheap toys which we treasured very much.
 The girls would probably get a doll and we would get a game and some sweets, and maybe one or two bars of chocolate and some nuts, and an apple. That was Christmas morning, which we thought was quite good. We always had a good Christmas dinner. A joint o
f pork or a fowl. In the afternoon Aunties and Uncles would come in for high tea and we'd have a party after tea and games and everybody would generally let their hair down, and have a jolly evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you go to Church on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 I can't
 say we were compelled to go. I think my sisters would go out of a sense of duty and loyalty to Church, but I don't remember ever being compelled to go to Church. When we were in our younger teens we would be expected to go round carol singing 'til about 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 1}}}one o'clock{\*\xmlclose}
 in the morning with the Sunday School, on Christmas Eve, and collect. And then we were allowed to lie in if we wanted to, but this generally didn't happen we were too excited, even in our teens. Christmas Day was... you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Yes, we had a violin - a very old violin which was the gift of someone who had played in the Halle Orchestra at one time. It was a family heirloom. I was given charge of it and I used to have lessons at school, out
 of school hours, which cost me 6d. a lesson. I remember having possibly twelve lessons and I got tired of it and just packed it in. Did anybody else try to play it? Yes my younger brother had a similar experience. I think he preserved a little bit more t
h
an I did but he fell by the wayside as regards music. Probably the violin was too difficult an instrument for youngsters to play. But we were certainly encouraged to be musical and as the family income grew, as we grew up, we ran to a piano and my younger
 sisters were encouraged to take lessons, two of them. But they never accomplished anything much, except to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6504091\charrsid15301266 play}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
 hymn tunes and the popular ballads of the day to which we used to sing, round the piano, but this was later on when we were in our late teens. W
e would buy the popular songs of the day. I don't mean the old-fashioned "Drink to me only with thine eyes" business and these popular song books that we had you know. My particular favourite was "The Mountains of Morne", I used to sing that as a solo and
 party piece. And my brother and I would sing "Watchman what of the night" that was a particular favourite, as a duet.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did any of your aunts and uncles come in to make music with you or was it just your parents and your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Wel
l at Christmas we each had our party piece, which was the same each Christmas. They all had their pieces to recite, you see, and were all expected to do their party piece on Christmas night and we used to enjoy it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did your parents ever play games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Oh yes. Indoor games in winter. Draughts, dominoes, ludo, snakes and ladders, can't remember any others. Oh my father would play games with us, yes. As regards outdoor sport, no. We used to make our own outdoor sport. When the cricket season s
tarted we'd go round all the neighbours and collect pennies to buy cricket bat and ball and we'd form a local cricket team with neighbourhood boys of our own age, from about the age of about ten onwards, and we used to have a cricket team which played on 
the spare ground. We'd collect enough pennies from fathers and mothers and neighbours for a cricket \{ILLEGIBLE\}
. We used to build our wickets of bricks and stones, but the team was the important thing. We used to have a cricket team which played various loc
al other gangs of boys. And when the football season started we would do the same. We'd generally go round and collect pennies and raise enough pennies to buy what we'd call a case ball, which was a proper football. And we used to have our own football te
a
m our local football team. And any time we could get out, which wasn't often enough, because I remember my mother insisting on I had to help with the washing-up and do things before going out to play. I'd come home from school and I had to do jobs around 
the house - perhaps one or two errands before tea at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 30}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 5}}}half past five{\*\xmlclose}
. After tea my sister and I would probably have to wash up and then we were allowed to go out to play. And we were fortunate to own a piece of spare ground in front of the house which we played cricket and football on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you have books about in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Yes. Certain kinds. These were censored pretty well. I was forbidden cheap magazines like the 'Magnet' and the 'Gem' these were considered to be no good at all, but they were ve
ry precious to us. And there was another popular one called 'The Boys Friend' and another about Sexton Blake, which were cheap weeklies. I think the 'Magnet' and the 'Gem' cost 1/2d but I was never allowed to buy these things. I got them secondhand, and I
 
liked to smuggle them into the house and read them in the privacy of my own bedroom. And even then I would get a lecture, this was not suitable, this was wrong. It was trash, my mother's favourite work. But we were encouraged to read books in the house, a
nd we had Sunday School prizes, books, and certain religious books. And the thing that came into the house every week was 'The Christian Herald' and that had a weekly serial by Silas Hocking or Joseph Hocking and we were encouraged to read that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3963118\charrsid15301266 I t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 hi
nk it was put as much trash as the boys friend when I look back on it, but nevertheless it had a \{ILLEGIBLE\} basis, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3963118\charrsid15301266 and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
it was accepted into the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What about newspapers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Just the local Bolton News, that came into the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You didn't have a morning paper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Do you remember your mother or father reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Yes I think my father read a bit. I wouldn't call him a well read man. He used to read his Bible. Both of them were Bible readers. And he used to read the Bible. I th
ink after we'd gone to bed, they used to have a session with the Bible nearly every night, but I'm guessing here because once or twice I had to come downstairs with tummy ache or something like that, and I would overhear them reading from the Bible or rel
igious literature of some sort.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did they ever read aloud to you, to the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. I don't think so. I don't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Do you remember there ever being a funeral in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. The funeral was very important. I remember my gran
dmother's funeral. She died when she was 65. Grandmother Benson. I was taken into see her as she lay dead - when she'd been laid out in bed and made to look nice and decent - we were taken in as children to look at her for the last time. And I remember th
e
 funeral was rather an important occasion. My grandmother had a big family; there was three brothers and four sisters and all these came to the funeral with their own families of children, which amounted to perhaps four or five coach loads of relatives. A
nd it was very important that she should be given a good funeral and a good headstone put on the grave. It stands out very clearly - I would have been nine years when grandmother died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What about mourning clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes we all had to wear black. We
 had to have a new suit. We had to have black suits all of us. There were my sister and brother and I to fit out. My sister would have a black dress and my brother and I would have black suits for grandmother's funeral.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Is there anything in the way the funeral was conducted that was different from the way they are done today?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
There was a great deal more ceremony. Today they seem to be formal affairs. I think my grandma's funeral was important because she was important in the family. An important 
person. We had to take her to church and there was an impressive service in church and another impressive service at the graveside, and everybody shed tears and it was quite an impressive afternoon, as far as we were concerned as children. We finished up 
with high tea in our house - we had a fairly big kitchen in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bloomfield Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and a good front sitting room and everybody came in. The people who came any distance went off without tea. Some of my aunties and uncles lived as far away as Horw
ich which was quite a distance in those days, and Leigh. That was another 6 miles but we used to think it was a long way to go. They would go off probably but I can remember some aunties and uncles coming to our house for tea after the funeral.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Were you taken out to visit your aunts and uncles, neighbours and friends when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Who would it be that would take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Father and mother together. Mostly on holidays - during the holiday period. We used to think it was quite
 an adventure to have a tram ride to Horwich to our cousins. Leigh was another place where we had cousins and we'd visit them during holidays some times and stay for a few days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What exactly do you mean by holiday periods?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Well there was Easter. We got so few holidays at the seaside as children. I remember one or two probably seaside holidays. 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose} holidays when the works was closed we mostly spent in trips. My father would take us to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Southport{\*\xmlclose}
 for the day or probably to Leigh for half a day, or Horwich. Or he would take us over {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Belmont{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and walk from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Belmont{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to Rivington and come back by tram. That was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12718837\charrsid15301266 sort}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
 of way we'd spend our holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would this apply to Bank Holidays and odd days during the holiday week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 That's right. Yes. Go
od Friday father would probably go to church, but we weren't compelled to go church on Good Friday, that was the day when mother would pack up sandwiches and as children we would go off on our own and spend the day on Rivington Pike or Belmont Moors or Al
ton Towers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 When you did get the chance to go away to the seaside for a holiday would this be all the family who would go together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 I can't remember all our family ever going on a holiday together. I can remember as a young child when there were 
only three of us in the family, the three children, having a seaside holiday at a place called Knott End where I think lodgings were fairly cheap and some fresh air and a change and the great joy there was to have a wagonette drive. I've a feeling we prob
a
bly went there two years in succession. I think we had two seaside holidays there and those were the only two seaside holidays I really remember. Although my mothers says she and my father took my sister and myself, when I was about three or four and she 
would be seven, to the Isle of Man. And we were all sick on the boat. But I don't know how long it was for.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 When you went to Knott End how long would that before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 That would be probably for a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 When were {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose} holidays at this time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 I think it was August.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How would you spend your Saturdays when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
We were left to our own devices on Saturdays. Saturday mornings we had to do the errands and help with the housework, clean the house. Saturday afternoons we w
ere free and we were left to our own devices. My earliest recollections was to go and watch cricket. The local cricket team. From a very early age I used to go and watch the local Sunday School cricket team. It was all sorts. I hadn't any money so I could
n't afford to go to a cricket match and pay to go in. Not even a penny. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose}
 and district cricket league we could go in for a penny but we just didn't have a penny to go in. So I used to go and watch the Sunday School Cricket Team. I can remember on one o
ccasion walking to Old Trafford and this was a school holiday. The High School holiday in August and a friend of mine and I we told our mother we would go out for the day and she would pack us jam sandwiches. We didn't tell her we were going to Old Traffo
r
d cricket ground. Might have been 11 then. And we would sit on a bridge and watch the boats come up the ship canel. Watch for boats to come up and that was a thrill to watch a big steamer come up the canel. And we would have our jam sandwiches on the cane
l
 bank. Then we would walk from there to Old Trafford cricket ground, wait for the gates to open to let the crowd came up after tea and the boys would then swarm in without paying - see the last hours cricket which was a reward in itself especially Johnny!
 Who was the famous {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Lancashire{\*\xmlclose}
 batsman of the day and the fast bowler who was a chap called Briersly. We would see these two operate and of course that made the day. Walking was one of the things we did. We prided ourselves on the distance we could walk... 
and then there was the walk home and if we'd two pence in our pockets we might have had a penny or twopence which we'd saved up for the occasion. Bound to do this probably two or three weeks before and the last penny would be spent on a halfpennyworth of 
chips and a bottle of pop on the way home somewhere - Clifton or Farnworth - one of the little shops coming from Manchester along the main road to Bolton. This was quite a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What about your Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh Sundays were very religiously observed. As children we went to Sunday School at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 30}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 9}}}half past nine{\*\xmlclose}
 in the morning and from the age of about ten or eleven we came out of Sunday School and went into church, and the younger ones would be allowed home at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 30}}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 10}}}half past ten{\*\xmlclose}. The older ones would file into Church at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 20}}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 10}}}twenty past ten{\*\xmlclose} for the Morning Service. Then there was Sunday School in the afternoon from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}
{\xmlattrvalue 30}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 2}}}half past two{\*\xmlclose} 'till {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 30}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}
{\xmlattrvalue 3}}}half past three{\*\xmlclose}. And then as children we were expected to go again at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 6}}
}six o'clock{\*\xmlclose} for a Children's service in the evening, the Evening Service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you have different clothes on for Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. Very important we had our Sunday best clothes on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did your parents allow you to play games at all on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 I suppose they would both go to church, would they, your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Mother would be busy cooking in the mornings. Mother and father would go to church in the evenings. Sunday afternoons father would go about various churchs talking to men's Bible classes - various places in the town district. And
 he would walk as far as Horwich to take a mens' class and nobody would persuade him to spend 2d. to go on the tram. He wouldn't. That was a crime to go on a tram on a Sunday. And he would walk both ways to take a mens' class say at Horwich from Astley Br
idge.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did your Sunday School organise outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Yes. To local places. We had one annual outing a year. This was what we called the Sunday School class picnic, which meant the Sunday School would take anything from ten to twenty scholars in the class and go to some country place like 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Rivington{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} or to Worsley, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Heaton{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 was another favourite for Sunday School picnics. Easy to get to by 1d. or 2d. tram rides, you'd get to them with a little walk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What other social activities were organized by the church?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Concerts mostly. Sunday School concerts and various branches of Sunday School activities like temperance society would organize their special gen in the form of a play - pointing out the use of strong drink and moral laws. I can remem
ber the favourite play of the temperance society was one called 'The Prodigal Son'. They used to publish short one act plays which had a moral and religious purpose behind them - I can't remember the publisher now, but these plays were quite frequently do
ne in Sunday School. The cricket club would have their concert, and the football club would organize a concert for the benefit of their own particular activity. The Church Lads' Brigade had a concert. The temperance society.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you belong to any of these?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
No. I used to want to join the Church Lads' Brigade but my mother used to think they were rather rough for me - the rougher end of the parish used to get in the Church Lads' Brigade. Out time then did. She didn't forbid it entirely but she used 
to discourage the idea. These lads came from the 'slummier' end of the parish, they were all very good lads most of 'em were killed in the 14-18 war, bless 'em but I wasn't encouraged to join.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you belong to the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What denomination was the Church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Church of England. All Souls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Was grace said at home at meal time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. Always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 And who was it that said it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Obviously you would be taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did your father take an interest at all in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
No. Not an active interest. He was active in his trade union, which was I think the foundry men's trade union, at this time. No I wouldn't say he was an active party member at all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 But he had his own views?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
He had his own particular views which was in those days called Lib-Lab, which was a sort of right wing Labour man if you like, but he would vote Liberal. In those days {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose}
 was represented by one liberal
 and one labour and they used to run together against the Conservatives, you see, and they called them Lib-Labs. They would be frowned upon by the extreme left of the labour movement and the socialist movement would think these were traitors, but my fathe
r had no room for the extreme socialist type of person. I think the association with atheists and atheism and so forth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What about your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Mother had no active interests outside her home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did she hold any particular political views?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
No I think what particular views she had she would get through the co-operative women's guild. I think she used to go there one night a week, when we were older and able to look after the younger children. My sister and I could stay and look after the y
ounger children while she went to the guild on Thursday night. That was her only outdoor activity apart from the Church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would you say that she tended towards the labour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh yes. I think she got political ideas through the women's guild. Not tha
t the women's guild had any party loyalties, I don't think, in those days it hadn't. There was no party loyalty. But there were various speakers who used to come to the guild I think and imparted what we termed as progressive ideas about politics.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Can you remember your mother and father voting in a General Election up to 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Yes. By 1918 they would both be voting labour. My father would certainly vote labour because the labour man prior to 1914 was a prominent local trade unionist and he would 
come on the loyalty of most active trade unionists in the town. He would be elected on a trade union vote, rather than on a party political vote I should think, before 1914. The 1918 election, well I was in the army in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}France{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and I don't remember much about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
In some places at that time people used to think they may lose their job or their home if they didn't vote according to the wishes of their employer, or somebody else. Would this apply at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 I don't think it affected out family. I've no 
recollections of any influences. I know it happened - you'd vote as your employer wished you to do. But in the textile industry and in the engineering industries in the town there was quite an independent attitude from work people. They were large enough 
to stand on their own and the trade union dominated their thinking.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Neither your father or mother were active members of a political party so it's unlikely they would do anything to help the party at election time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. They wouldn't do that. They would be sympathetic to the Labour Party but that was about the end of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Well, now, you've told me a little bit about your parents other interests. Your mother only went out to her co-operative women's guild, did she? Did she ever go out to enjoy herself, apart from that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
As we grew up, and were teenagers, yes, she would leave us in charge of the younger ones and go to a Sunday School meeting or Sunday School concert in the evening, something like that. She would think that was a pleasant nig
ht out and a relief from domestic chores.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Who would she go with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 She'd go by herself. She'd meet other people there. See her friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did your father ever go out just for the purpose of enjoying himself? Rather than taking an active part in the union.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
No. All his activities were connected with some purpose. He was active in the temperance movement, in the trade union movement, and in the co-operative. I should say that the co-operative commanded quite a lot of his time. And I think as 
we grew older the co-operative society took over from the church in his part-time priorities. He was elected as a member of the education committee and I think this made demands on his time - he would have a committee meeting once a week, as a result of t
h
at he would have one or two, possibly three nights, taking children's classes in industrial history or what he called co-operation the history and principles of the co-operative movement. They were mostly school children from 10, 11, 12. There were childr
e
n's groups and they used to attend these classes once a week in various parts of the town and my father and various other members of the committee would go and talk to them about the co-operative movement and how it was formed and the background to it. Th
e
 story of Robert Owen and the Chartist movement and they had to make it part of their business to know about these people. To read about them. And my father would probably spend two or three hours in preparation to take these classes reading up his indust
rial history. About the \{ILLEGIBLE\} pioneers and \{ILLEGIBLE\} the Christian Socialists and Kingsley and he had to get an interest about these people and had to tell children what these people wanted to do, what they were trying to do.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did he do anything of the same sort with adult groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Yes. He would talk to an adult group on co-operative affairs. He was in demand as a speaker at various co-operative guilds. Men's guilds and Women's Guilds. There was a men's Guild which was formed much later dur
ing the 14-18 war. He helped to form what was called a Men's Guild which grew into quite an important body. I think it is defant now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would that be just groups in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No he would go about to places like Horwich and Leigh and Westhoughton talking to branch groups of men.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Obviously your father being a temperance man would not go to pubs at all, would he? Or did he go to try to reform the ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. I think he may have to go to one or two pubs in regard to trade union work because pub
s were a favourite meeting ground for the committee - the trade union committee. He may have to go to places that was very much against his grain and he was always agitating that trade union meetings shouldn't go to public houses. I remember him having a 
thing about this.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did he belong to any club at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
No. The only club, and he wasn't a very active member, was a Reccabites Club was the sick club. They paid sick benefits. He wasn't active in it but he was a member, so that if he did fall on evi
l times there would be a few shillings coming in from the sick club.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did your father or mother belong to any other type of savings club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No I don't think so. They paid their 1d. a week insurance clubs, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did your father take part in any sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 And he wouldn't go as a watcher to anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. Only in what I would call the course of duty. If the men's guild had a bowling tournament he would go and show his interests there.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 But would he do anything like going to the races?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. Oh dear me, no. That was the devils work!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Now we're back to you and your brothers and sisters. How did you get on together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 On the whole very well I think. I think we used to have little bits of jealousies and quarrels, mo
st families do, but they don't stand out as being anything. I think I sometimes used to resent having to take care, when I wanted to do things on my own I would resent having to take care of my younger brothers and sisters: take them out - take them with 
me where I happened to be going or do a spot of pram pushing when there were babies to be taken out. I used to be put on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Was there any brother or sister that you felt particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You used to play together? Would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Up to a certain age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you play with neighbour's children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Change sometimes. I used to resent that and probably. Oh yes, very much so. I mean you got to the age of six, seven, eight, you found your own friends, amongst the neighbours' children.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 And you would play with them rather than with your own family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. There were different age groups in your own family so you would find someone of your own age to play with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Now you said you had a piece of ground in front of the house where you could play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you play anywhere else besides there, either in the house or yard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh in the parks. We would go and play in the parks on occasions. Swings in the park. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} wasn't far away and as boys we would go
 there and swing on the parallel bars and play on the swings and sometimes play cricket on the grass there. Sometimes when four or five of us would make a small cricket team up and go in the park and challenge four or five other boys, and play a game of c
ricket. That was quite frequent in the school holidays. But this was mainly during the four weeks school holidays we had in August. This was an activity - every afternoon we would think of a different park to go to. We'd go down to the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} sometimes
. Perhaps a group of four or five boys and take a bat and ball and look for another small group of boys to challenge to a game of cricket.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you ever go into children's homes to play? And did other children come into yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Not very often. No.
 Occasionally we might bring a friend but we didn't look upon the home as a place to play in at all except when father could spare a few minutes to play a game of draughts or teach us something like that. No I don't remember going to neighbours' houses to
 play. Except as you got older as you got your own particular friend you might have one particular friend and you'd go in his house and he'd come in yours. 11 or 12.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 That would be when you were getting a little bit older wouldn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. You wou
ld get attached to one particular boy and you would take him home sometimes to tea and his mother would perhaps invite you to tea sometimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You told me about when you were younger playing you\rquote re your mother's pearl buttons and marbles and so on. What
 other sorts of games would you have played at that age?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
There was all sorts of boys games. Rough games. One was know as duck stone. You built a little pyramid of stones and then put on stone on the top and you used to have to pick stones, sizeable 
stones which you could get in your fist, and try and knock the top stone off. And if you did that ... I've forgotten how we used to play this. There used to be come running in it, the boy who was out who was sort of victim. You used to try and knock the c
o
lumn of stones down and while the boy who was the victim was rebuilding it you'd used to have to run from corner to corner while he was rebuilding. It was like a game of rounders in a way. Yes. It had associations with rounders. Rounders was a popular gam
e
; we had another name for it though, rounders. Yes rounders, duck stone and certain jumping games - we had one we used to call ride a kench, this was played in teams of three or four boys and the boys would go down and hold each other behind, form a sort 
o
f chain, and you used to have to jump on their backs. If there were three boys you would aim at going in one jump on to the top boy's back, you see, over these two (you'd used these two as levers) to get on to the third boy. So that your team of three or 
f
our, playing say three a side, the three of you would have to jump on the three boys backs and if they collapsed they'd lost the game, you see. And there were penalties to pay, forfeits probably a kick in the pants or something like that. Another game we 
used to chase each other in teams and we used to do this to deliberately annoy some group of boys, to get chased and this would mean a real hare and hounds all round the streets and sometimes out into the country.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played when you were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Oh yes. We'd get punished for tearing clothes. We sometimes got a tear and mother would administer a slap over the head, or something like that, and 'get off to bed'. She'd show her disgust, you see, if we tore our clot
hes. But so long as we came in and cleaned ourselves up and didn't leave any dirt in the house. There was always a back way into the house, which if we had any mud on our clothes it was a good thing to get it cleaned off before you went into the house.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Were you free to play with anybody you pleased.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 More or less, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Was there any type of child that you were ever discouraged from playing with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Not really. We would sometimes be advised to keep away from a certain clique or the 'lamb brow' lot. One hotel on the corner of 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Seymour Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} is called. The Lamb Hotel and the road that runs up there is called {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Old Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. But we in our boyhood days it was known as the lamb brow for some reason or other, and it was a rather slummy area with a rough l
ot of lads. Big catholic families very roughly brought up, some of them hadn't any footwear. We used to challenge them to our patch to play football or cricket and this would generally \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 end with stone throwing going on and this was terribly disc
ouraged. Possibly for two reasons. First of all these lads didn't hesitate to use bad language which we were never permitted. And second because the stone throwing usually ended in somebody's window being broken and this would mean we forfeited pocket mon
e
y until the window was paid for, so that there was discouragement to associate with this group of boys. But it never prevented us because there was something of a challenge here, you see, if it came to a fight we were as good as they were. This would invo
lve sometimes interference by parents these sort of stone-throwing fights, and sometimes fisticu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10245280\charrsid15301266 ff}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
s or wrestling would be broken up by parents.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You say you would have liked to have belonged to the Church Lads' Brigade. Did you belong to any youth organisations at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. Only Band of Hope which was a sort of Monday night meeting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Can you tell me something about how you spent your free time when you were at school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you have any hobbies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. We had rabbits. My brother was ver
y fond of keeping pets. I wasn't particularly keen but I remember we shared a common interest in rabbits for a short period. I got tired of rabbits; my brother kept them and he followed on with guinea pigs and hens and he always had an interest in livesto
c
k. But not me. I was very fond of reading and at an early age I joined a local library in Astley Bridge which was then one of the new Carnegie libraries and this was a real treasure to me as a boy to go in there and to be able to get a book, at the age of
 
ten or eleven, and reading was mostly adventure stories and school stories by popular authors of the day. Henty stories, adventure stories, school stories of the time. I was allowed to read these in the house, these were all right, because they were out o
f the public library. These were on a higher plain then the penny dreadfuls and the 1/2d. Magnets and Gems, you see. I can remember spending quite a lot of my time reading.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you collect anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. I don't think so. No. I was never a collector.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You wouldn't have a garden then would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Just a small hankerchief garden in front of the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you do any gardening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. Not really. My father used to keep it tidy. And put a few pansies in and lobelia and probably bedding 
out plants just in the front garden and they used to keep the privet... each garden was surrounded by a privet hedge which had to be clipped and I don't remember as a boy ever doing any gardening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You liked outdoor activities like walking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh yes, very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What about fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
No. Except with a jam jar and a little net. One of the favourite haunts was Barrow Bridge, over here, and there used to be a boating pond there and there was small fish in there we could sometimes catch with a n
et and in the stream there was little minnows and gudgeons, but you couldn't call it fishing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you go any boating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No you couldn't afford to. Except when we were about ten or eleven we'd save our pennies we got from aunties and uncles and sh
are a boat on Barrow Bridge lake, as a treat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You took part in cricket and football did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 As a boy, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Any other sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you go to any theatres?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No theatres were taboo. Another place for the devil.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Obviously the same would be true of music halls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes music halls were dens of inquity.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Concerts? You went to the Sunday School concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. That's about all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You didn't go to any others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Not as children. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What about the cinema?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 From 1904 when the first cinema projectors were used in the fair grounds on the town hall square in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place
}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose}. The cinema used to come with a 1d. show. And we used to have a cinema at what was then the temperance hall in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose}, which only came on
 Saturday afternoons. I don't say we were discouraged from going but we never had any money to go. But if we could raise 1d. as children we might go to the temperence hall on Saturday afternoon and see these very early films. 'Charles Peace' was one of th
em and 'The Great Train Robbery' I think, was another one, and some 'mock up' of the Boer War was another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What about the fair? Did your parents allow you to go the fair?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Reluctantly, yes. We were allowed to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What about a circus.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No, we were discouraged. I can't recall them. Only a sort of Wild Beast Shows we used to call them round the fair in New Year, in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose}. There was a wild beast show and a show where you could go and watch as we called them, Living Pictures. This would cost at 1d. It was a question of pocket money this.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Your pocket money was a weekly 1/2d. after you'd done your Saturday chores?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. Up to the age of twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Was there anything else you spent the money on other than the things you've been telling me?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
No, only sweets. Any extra amusements came from pennies that were given you by aunties and uncles. Or maybe for doing errands for some of the neighbours. If someone wanted somebody to run errands perhaps on Saturday morning you would get a 1/2d
. or a 1d., and these we used to guard very preciously and save them 'till we got perhaps 3d. which was quite a lot of money and then we blew this on a fair or something, or walking to Old Trafford with 2d. in your pocket.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you ever save money to buy anything special with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
The first I remember trying to save money was trying to buy a bicycle and this was a second hand one, and I was in my early teens, then thirteen.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 This was the one that you shared with your brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did anyone outside the home help your mother to look after the house or family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Oh yes. When mother was confined. I can remember the three younger children being born. And when one of these were born auntie used to come in. She hadn't any children, she 
was an elderly aunt with no family of her own, and was the standby of the family when things were a bit tight and mother was poorly or confined. All the children were born in the house and auntie used to come along and act as home help.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Was your routine disrupted in any other way when one of the children was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Not really. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would anybody come in at any other time or only when your mother was ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. The next door neighbour might pop in sometimes to see if there was anything if 
my mother was ill or just off colour. We were trained to do what we could from an early age and to be independent and to cook our own breakfasts. If mother was poorly we could go downstairs and make our own porridge, and make some toast and tea and get of
f to school ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Apart from your aunt living nearby, did you have other relatives living close?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Oh yes, all my mother's brothers and sisters were - their relationships was very close. But their own particular lives, their own particular act
ivities didn't permit of attendance on each other at times of sickness. No. They all had their own families to look after. The only aunty who was a regular helper in the house was one who hadn't any children of her own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you see your relatives frequently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Very frequently. Yes. Sunday nights was an occasion when they used to visit. A visiting night. People would come in after church and stay until perhaps {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 10}}}ten o'clock{\*\xmlclose} or half past. We would be packed off to bed of course at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 9}}}nine o'clock{\*\xmlclose}. But visiting on Sunday evening or sometimes a Saturday evening was quite a common practice, between relatives.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What about friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 And friends. Yes. Friends of the family used to come and visit us in the evenings - Saturday and Sunday evenings.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did your parents share their friends or did your mother have her own particular friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
I think they were shared friends. One's friends were both's friends. I don't think there was any discrimination between friends. They were all welcome. They were mostly visiting couples.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 And would your parents go and visit them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 People that were invited into the house, would they be invited for a meal?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Sometimes on Sundays, yes. They may be invited to tea on Sundays. But mostly it was a 
case of a cup of tea and sandwiches or biscuits in the evening or something like that in the evening. On occasions they'd be invited to tea, especially if they came over from Horwich or Leigh, they would come to tea on Sunday. We'd invite them to tea.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What about people calling in casually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 The door was always open for casual visitors.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would people who called in casually be offered something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Mother would say 'Have a cup of tea'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did people call in casually without an invitation quite often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Mostly friends of mother's in the afternoon might come over for an afternoon cup of tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would neighbours drop in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes the next door neighbour. But mostly the neighbourliness was done over the back yard wall. Just a small brick 
or wooden partition between the two houses and mother would have a gossip over the yard wall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 There wasn't any dropping into each others houses and having a cup of tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 On occasions yes. Neighbours used to drop in just like that and pass the tim
e of the day. And with mother not being well they'd come in "How's your mother" "Oh come in, She's all right. She'd like to talk to you - for a little gossip"
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Its often said that at that time people used to make their own amusements, and I think from 
what you've said this seems to be pretty well true. Did your parents do anything in particular when they go together with their friends and relatives, in the way of say making music or playing games, or anything like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Only at Christmas. Except w
hen we were in our late teens (16, 17 and 18) we were allowed to bring friends in and we would get round the piano and sing and that was encouraged - as long as we sang the right stuff, you see. We started with hymns. This happened mostly on Sundays, afte
r church, and one had to be very careful with your repertoire that you sang the right }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10245280\charrsid15301266 song}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266  with a good moral tone, you see.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Many people divide society into different social classes. In the time up to 1918 did you think of some people as belonging to o
ne class and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh yes. Well there was the wealthy class, the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Chorley New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} people and the people that lived up {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Seymour Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, which was a residential area. There were certain residential areas, and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Seymour Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} in those days was one 
of them, where the professional classes lived, and they were a class on their own. The school master from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}
Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} school lived up there; and the local mill owner Colonel Hesketh who was one of the important {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose} citizens, he lived in a big house th
ere. There were some other mill owners, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15754262\charrsid15301266 Mallinsons, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 who had mills and beach works, and there were the aristocrats of 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 in those days. Particularly Colonel Hesketh. And the Ashworths, they were also cotton mill owners. These were the upper class
 as far as we knew, we didn't know any nobility, they weren't titled people. The Colonels and the Captains were mostly the territorial or result of volunteer service, that they had these titles; mostly mill owners, industrialists, with their big houses an
d
 stables and the back - these were the aristocrats the really top class as we knew in those days. Then there was of course the distinct professional classes - the doctors and the solicitors and the school masters, who we thought were a class on their own 
- the professional classes. We, I suppose, thought ourselves as the respectable working class; we were a little bit above the labouring class who lived in the poorer districts of the town.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Were you taught to treat people of a particular class differen
tly from people of another? Thinking say of the wealthy or top class people? Like Colonel Hesketh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You'd have to raise your cap, or something like this, would you, if you saw him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes, you would do as a mark of respect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Were there any other people that you would have to show a mark of respect to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No, I don't think so, except the Minister, the Parson and the school master.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Was there anybody that you had to call 'sir' or 'madam'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You would do. But I don't say you ha
d to. But you would call them 'sir' or 'madam' out of respect. You'd always say 'sir' to the headmaster. Our contact with these people would be very limited, it would be limited to special occasions like when they might come along to present Sunday School
 prizes and then you would say "Thank you 'sir'". The girls would give a little bow to show how grateful they were for all the small gifts they used to get. I can remember Lord Leverhulme distributing gifts. This was when he had 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Lever{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And I was spendi
ng Christmas there. My father was poorly then - my father was in hospital one Christmas. And my sister and I were sent off to Horwich to stay with cousins. And Lady Lever - I don't know if she was Lady Lever then - the wife of Sir William Lever. I think h
e might be Sir William in those days but we knew him as Billy Lever, he was making his thousands then. And she was a very famous type and she would come into the houses of the Horwich people who lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Rivington{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} then. And I remember we got gifts on t
his occasion, very simple Christmas gifts, from Lady Lever. Simply because my uncle and aunt and cousines used to go to the same church as Lady Lever did. I don't think she was Lady Lever. She was Mrs. Lever then. They were important people.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 In your particular district you would consider people like Colonel Hesketh the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Colonel Hesketh yes. He was the most important person in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName
}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Very worthy citizen of the town, of course. He was the Mayor of the town and stood for Parliament on one occasion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 So he was important for these sort of reasons not just because he was wealthy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh yes he was wealth and also a big employer of labour. He had these big mills in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} then - and one or two other mills. I think, smaller mills. But he was the main employer of labour in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} in the cotton spinning industry. And also a pillar of the church, 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What sort of people, apart from teachers, doctors, etc., that you considered to be the 
professional classes - are there any others that you would put in that particular group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would you call them strictly professional classes?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh I should say that those were the people who we thought were middle class, 
above our particular ... We considered these important people. They did a job in their own particular way, they would attend church and show their interest in church activities. We didn't go to the village church in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, we went to All Saints. I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}
Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} school. They always seemed to take an interest in the affairs of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Astley
{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and I suppose in local civic affairs. They always seemed to have some sort of interest these people. They fulfilled a purpose in life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What sort of people would they associate with? Would they associate with anybody about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Oh no no. They would have their own social circle. On Sundays they would come down to perhaps our level with regards going to church, and probably act as superintendent in Sund
ay School sometimes. They would be prominent on Sunday School anniversaries and donating subscriptions in the form of guineas and pennies. It was partly wealth and partly the better education; they were looked upon as better educated people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What sort of people for instance would the clergy associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Their flock included all classes, didn't it. I suppose in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceName}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} society the vicar would quite often be in Colonel Hesketh's house and vice versa. Colonel Hesketh being a big churchman and the vicar of 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 was considered an important person and in the same type of class as Colonel Hesketh and the other people. But on the other hand I suppose he visited the parishioners on occasions, especially during sick periods. But we used to
 look upon the vicar and the curate as somebody very important.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What about the teachers - the headmaster and the teachers at the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 I suppose they would have their own particular friends and social acquaintances. The more wealthy church pat
rons. The headmaster of a place like Astley Bridge he was expected to take his place in church activities and of course he would in the course of duty come in contact with people like the vicar, and Colonel Hesketh and the wealthier sections of the congre
gation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Were there any farmers about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
No I don't think so. I don't think you would find any farmers active in social activities at all, the farmers were very much a class unto themselves. There were farmers about on the fringe of the village, of 
course. We used to rely on milk production, deliver milk, take the milk round to the houses in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and maybe all round the town. They used to come down with a horse and milk load. But their social life was very much confined to themselves. They were a very exclusive class to themselves.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would you say there was much mixing between the different professional groups within the same class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 I wouldn't know. I couldn't tell you. There would be a certain amount of mixing politically because t
here was certain political activities they had in common and I should think that any social activities those days would be centred round the Conservative political party in those days and the Liberal party. Two distinct groups and the groups would contain
 elements of various classes of people. And there would be a common meeting ground here with common political party interests.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Going on to your class, that you described as the respectable working class, what sort of people would belong to your group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Mostly artisan and craftsmen; cotton spinners would be included. The man in the cotton mill who was a sort of an employer in his own right. He was a spinner of what was known as a wheel gate and he employed two assistants - a side piece and a little
 piecer - and he used to pay these from his own earnings, so he was a sort of employer you see. He was employed by the mill owner and over him would be a mill manager. Possibly what was termed an overlooker. I think he was an overlooker overlooking the se
ction of the mill in which the cotton spinning was done. Now then, there would be the cotton spinners who were a very important social group of their own, and they would be in the earnings of 50/- to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid294071 \'a3}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 3 a week, the wealthy section of the working class peopl
e in those days. Then there would be the fitters and the engineers. Father was in the foundry - he was a craftsman, a moulder. In the foundry there were different skilled crafts:- moulders, pattern makers, fitters and one or two others, who had served the
ir time at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10245280\charrsid15301266 a particular}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
 trade. These were a class on their own, and would consider themselves somewhat distinct from the labouring classes. The people who used to do the fetching and carrying, and the assistants.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You speak of the cotton spinners being 
a class on their own, and people like engineers and fitters being a class on their own; would they in fact meet together on level grounds socially?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 They weren't exclusive in that sense?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. They would all mix socially. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What about the labouring class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
These were respectable labourers who would mix in various church activities I suppose, who would be considered religious in the religious life of the church, who took part in the religious life of the church. You would m
ix with them, you wouldn't look down on them in any shape or form. The only people you'd look down on was the people who used to drink and neglect their family life - their wives and children. These were the people you'd look down on. But the average labo
urer who was probably earning 18/- to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid294071 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
1 a week, and was trying to do the best he could for his family, there was no snobbish ideas about this at all. Oh no. The only people we used to think were a bit low were the people who used to go into pubs, who used 
to drink on Saturday nights and spend their money on gambling, on horses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 The people who would go to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Church{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, they would be a mixed congregation of all the different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Your church, All Souls, would that be the same?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
The congregation socially, there wouldn't be the same element of aristocracy at All Souls. It was more in the working class part of the town, round what I call the working class perimeter of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose}. 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was more in the residential part yo
u see. You got in the working class perimeter of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose}
 which was centered within about 3/4 mile to a mile from the Town Hall. These were mostly what I would call typical slum dwellings where there were working class terraced houses, inhabited mostly by th
e lower income groups who would be earning 25/- to 30/- a week doing various jobs. Not altogether unskilled jobs, things like bus conductors, milk roundsmen, shop assistants and labourers too, that were very careful and wanted a decent life for their fami
l
ies. And these would be the people. We had a few business people at All Souls, shop keeping type of people, but I don't think we had any of the wealthy. I don't remember any doctors, lawyers, or solicitors, any of that type of people coming. It was a typi
cal working class parish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What sort of people would the shop keepers associate with? Who were their friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 I think a lot of them that went to church would confine their social activities to the church. They probably wouldn't admit it but I supp
ose business interest had a lot to do here, if you went to church and you had a shop in the parish, it was important. You used to patronise the shop because you know Mr. So and So, who happened to be a Sunday School teacher or superintendent. I suppose so
me of them had their own particular club life - the conservative club or liberal club - those were the social centres of the day. But quite a large proportion of them would belong to some church, either the non - conformist or the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Church{\*\xmlclose} of England.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Do you know much about the non conformist and catholic communities?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Not a great deal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What sort of people would go to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 A fairly good cross section of working class people and one or two of the trades people type. I don't think they co
mmanded many of what we called the better class people, what we might term the middle class or higher middle class, or the manufacturing classes of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose}
. I don't suppose many of them were non-conformists, one or two might be. Lever was of course - Lever 
himself built two or three congregational churches out of his money. But the non conformists were mostly very sincere working class people or trades people, with maybe one or two interested people from the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10122088\charrsid15301266 other, But I don't think they dominated}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 . I think t
hey were, dominated by the respectable working class people, nonconformists, who couldn't accept the prayer book, \{ILLEGIBLE\} about the prayer book. Who found the non conformist service more attractive than the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}
}Church{\*\xmlclose} of England.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Was there a strong catholic community in that part of the town?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12339559\charrsid15301266 In Bolton yes, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton
{\*\xmlclose}\rquote s very shory }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 In Astley Bridge there was a catholic community. Mostly the poorer element of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} were Catholics. I think we used to despise them a little bit. I don't know 
why. In fact one of my early girl friends was a catholic and this was very much frowned upon both by her parents and mine.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Where you lived in Astley Bridge, would you say that all the people in the lower class, the labouring class, would have the sam
e standard of living, or would you say they were different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh no. They were on much lower standard of living.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Within the class, would different categories have different standards of living would you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Well I should think there was an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12339559\charrsid15301266 Christian }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12979227\charrsid15301266 standard}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266  of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12979227\charrsid15301266 thi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
ng and a labouring class standard of living broadly speaking. Well the working class generally depended on their children leaving school and supplementing the family income, before what we called a 'good standard of living' was rea
ched. Most families had a minimum of three children and it could go up to eight, nine or ten in the family. And these were the people who really had a struggle. They'd buy second hand clothes and go to the rummage sales. I don't think it depended so much 
o
n income as the size of the family and the needs of the family and what parents were prepared to do for their families and what they were prepared to sacrifice for families. Now I wouldn't say that this sort of attitude, concern for the family welfare, wa
s
 confined to the artisan classes; because the labourers, many of them, were anxious that their families should have a chance. There was no ideas of birth control or anything like that and the mother of a labouring class with four, five, or six children re
ally had a tough time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Is there any family of that kind that you can remember that you can describe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Oh yes. Several. Many families who needed help and were often helped by my own parents. My father, one of the places he used to visit, he did a fair amount of mission work in the slum areas of Brunel Ford. The mission was known as the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Brunel Street{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Mission{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and my father would help a lot of people there who came to the mission in need of material help. He would help them wherever he could and my mo
ther would. They used to think this was part of their Christian obligation to help people, and they would do so. My father would help to organize subscriptions for his own particular workmates who were down on their own particular work. They'd have a whip
 round and help people who really needed it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would you say that your mother was class conscious at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
No. Or my father. I wouldn't say he was class conscious at all. No. We weren't class conscious, we recognized these people for what they were. They had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would you say it was possible in those days to move from one social class into another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Very difficult. It did happen occasionally. There was a certain gentleman who became to be known as Sir John Horden, a mill owner. He came out of 
a very poor family and he certainly rose socially to the top because he was the type. He was the Billy Lever type who could organize, take risks. Sir John Horden was a distant relative of mine through marriage. His own brothers and sisters lived typical w
orking class lives, but he rose. He became a mill manager, then a mill owner. I think he emigrated from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}
 to Leigh and founded a cotton mill there and became a very important person in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Lancashire{\*\xmlclose} life. Money and they were respected because they took an interest, a sort of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11940788\charrsid15301266 benevolent i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 nterest in the affairs of people in their own. The usual thing was that his sons didn't follow suit and they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10122088\charrsid15301266 dissipated}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266  their father's fortune. But it was very unusual and very difficult. Those were exceptional cases
, for a boy to pull himself by his own boot straps, we used to say, from clogs to clogs in three generations. But they were very rare cases these. Bill Lever was one of them of course Sir John Horden was another when I knew personally. There were one or t
wo other people who rose to the top through their own }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10122088\charrsid15301266 efforts}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
; their own commercial and industrial efforts. They must have had some sort of brain and dedication to money making.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Can you remember anybody who moved in the opposite direction, who started off higher up the scale?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Oh yes. Mostly through drink. Colonel Herketh had three sons, who were more or less fond of horses and dogs. And one of his sons was Colonel of the territorials, I think he fell addicted to drink. He was Colonel of the local
 territorials in the 1914-18 war and had to be brought home as a nervous wreck I think. There was a feeling that, well as the man who had made his own way felt that his own family mustn't go through what he'd done; he used to pamper them and this was bad 
for their own moral fibre.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Can you remember anybody that you would describe as a 'real gentleman' or a 'real lady'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Colonel Hesketh. We used to lock upon him as a gentleman in every sense of the word. And the school master, too, I suppose; a gent
leman in his own particular way. A discipline I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 school and he was the authority in the school in his time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What did you think of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 We used to fea
r him. As boys we would occasionally get into minor trouble. We used to make fun of the night watchman and that sort of thing and I remember once getting into real trouble with a policeman, was when we thought it great fun to turn his hut over, and he bro
u
ght the local bobby on to the job and this involved calling at certain boys' houses. One of them was mine and the policeman knocked at the door, I had gone to bed, and I was brought downstairs and questioned by the policeman was I in this gang that turned
 
over the watchman's hut. And this was a terrible thing in our family. A policeman should knock at our door. And the local police sergeant was a man we feared very much indeed, because we used to sometimes climb over walls to get into a football match or a
 cricket match or in to the local village show. Try to get the through hedges and that sort of thing. And the policeman would pounce then and he'd administer his own punishment on the spot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did your mother ever say 'I'll call a policeman', when you were children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
She'd say, "Well if you do that sort of thing you'll get into the hands of the police." She would say what sort of things were a crime and point out certain things must not be done, or the policeman would be after you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How do you think the policeman treated people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Very well on the whole, I think. I think his job was mainly looking after drunks Saturday nights and Friday nights. There wasn't a lot of crime not as we know it today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Do you think he treated people fairly or was he a bit harsh?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Well if the local policeman caught you doing something you shouldn't do he'd administer, I've been turned over a policeman's knee and thrashed for trying to climb over a wall, where you know, there used to be a big stone wall aroun
d there and we used to play football over it. And because I didn't have a penny I'd climb on this wall and watch it you see. Oh yes, I remember being pulled down from this wall on {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
Street}}Moss Bank Way{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And over there, I can remember being pulled down off that wal
l and thrashed by a policeman; probably for my own good because it was a fairly high wall. I don't know whether it still is, to watch football. We would trespass sometimes and the policeman would be on his beat and he'd catch us and he'd administer punish
ment on the spot, and that was the end of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 The home that you lived in, was it rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Our second home was bought through the co-op housing, like hundreds of other homes in Bolton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What about your earlier one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 That was rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you ever see anything of the landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 He used to call for his rent on Saturday mornings, regularly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 In person - he was a local man was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 I think so, as far as I know. I wouldn't know. I was only very young when we left that house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You probably wouldn't remember how he was as a landlord, whether he was a good one or a bad one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
I think he was good in his own particular way. He used to collect the rent, and would do the outside repairs, see the house was kept in good condition
. I don't know about interior repairs whether we had to pay for them or not, I should imagine we did. Paper hanging would come once every six or seven years I should imagine and do what we called the decorating but who paid for that I wouldn't know. In ge
n
eral you would feel that he fulfilled his obligations. Yes. I should say he did. I think he performed quite a useful function because he would let him house for four or five shillings a week and for his own interest he would see that it was kept in good r
epair outside.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 It sounds as if your parents did have a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 In the early days when we were young, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What did you think about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 We had no particular views. We accepted it as the ordinary life of our particular family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You took it upon yourselves to try to supplement things by taking on these jobs like paper round and such like?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. This was an important contribution to the family. The two-shillings a week I earned as a paper boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 In the early days were you ever badly off enough to need help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Yes. But my mother would never ask for it. My recollections were that we had to be content with soup when father was out of work, or on strike. We'd known then. Mother would say, "Well that's all 
you can have." It was probably a bowl of soup made of bone and vegetables, and this we knew was because father was out of work. And we just accepted it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Were you given lessons by one of your parents, a tutor or governess?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How old were you when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Was that all day - morning and afternoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 About what times did you start and finish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}
{\xmlattrvalue 9}}}Nine o'clock{\*\xmlclose} 'til twelve and two 'til four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What kind of a school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 My first school was {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Chalfont{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Street{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, a council school. Then we moved over the bridge, as we used to call it, which was a move up in social life, to our own house. Then we went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} school, which was a Church of England school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 And both these would be mixed schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Which of these were you at the longest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Astley Bridge.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How long did it take you to get to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Two or three minutes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Were you ever escorted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Don't remember. We used to go on our own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What did you think about school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
We looked upon it as a duty to learn our lessons and become proficient in the three Rs. And the great idea was to get a Scholarship to, what we called, the higher grade school. The {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Secondary School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. I remember sitting for scholarship to the free higher educational school, which was known as the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Municipal{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Secondary School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Great Moore Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. I won the scholarship to go there, but that involved keeping me there for four years, or three years at the least, you 
undertook to keep the child there 'till fifteen or sixteen. And this was a question of domestic economy again, and in my case my mother couldn't afford to let me take up the scholarship. She was very distressed about it. I accepted it seeing the distress 
which she showed about this and I said 'Don't worry I'll go and get myself and job.'
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You yourself had no particular regrets about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Afterwards, yes. It was one of the jealousies that I had with my younger brothers and sisters. At least two of t
hem won scholarships and went to the secondary school. And afterwards I felt rather envious and felt that life wasn't really - this was very much later of course. But no I just accepted that I'd got to go out to work as soon as my school days were over, w
hich was then at the age of thirteen. My eldest sister accepted the fact that she must go and work half-time in the weaving shed, as a half-timer, which she did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you like school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Not particularly. I liked some of it. I was interested in Histo
ry and Geography and I liked these things. I used to think Arithmetic was a bit of a bore but I used to do tolerably well at it. I did very well at school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You didn't dislike school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. I just accepted it as part of life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Some we liked and some we didn't. Some we respected and some we didn't. A lot depended on the teacher's personality. Whether the teacher was a friendly type and an encouraging type or whether he or she looked upon the cane as the 
sole means of controlling you. Some of them did, of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What would you regard as a friendly teacher in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 One who would give you a smile now and again, especially if it was a lady teacher. And come and encourage you and say 'That's 
very nice.", "That's a good drawing you've done." Or "That's a good essay you've written". This sort of encouragement we used to value very much. This was the sort of teacher we liked. The sort of teacher we didn't like was "No, that's terrible, come over
 and take the cane, you've not tried your best." You used to be punished and this was the sort of thing was used to hate. They were a mixed crew, the teachers in those days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did they used to emphasise particular things as being important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Yes. Getting on and getting a scholarship was very important. This was a real honour to the school. And the one or two bright boys who reached {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Grammar School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} these were the cream of the society. These were the important people. When you're about t
he age of 11 and you begin to show signs of intelligence you were picked out and joined a scholarship class. This meant extra tuition after school hours. The headmaster used to take an interest here I suppose for the honour of the school. You'd be encoura
g
ed to study and do a little bit of homework. Then you were sent in to enter for the very limited number of scholarships that were going you see. There was the Church Institute which was a higher educational establishment run by the church and then there w
as the Bolton School, grammar school, which was the boys school and the Higher Grade School which was mixed and to get a scholarship was a real aim of life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did they emphasise such things as manners and tidiness and punctuality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 As much as scholastic achievement?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Yes. Hygiene and cleanliness - we used to form into ranks in the school yard and the teacher would go round and look at your clogs to see whether they had been cleaned. And whether your hands were clean. And punishment
 if you went with dirty hands or clogs. This was the cane again. Your hands and clogs would be inspected before you went into school, the teacher would walk round the ranks and look to see whether you'd polished your clogs that morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What about manners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Yes. Manners were taught. Good behaviour yes. We had Religious Instruction every morning which included behaviour - 'Honour thy father and thy mother'. Very important. The 10 Commandments were important. Prayer book was important, catechism was important.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did they pay any attention to the way children spoke?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Not particularly. No. Except of course we were taught to sound our Hs in English lessons. That was important.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 If you did something that was disapproved of you would have some form of punishment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. The cane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You would be caned for bad work and dirty clogs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What other sorts of things would merit the cane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Talking in class. Or to laugh or interrupt a teacher. Or if the teacher left the room and
 came back to find everyone chattering she'd pounce on somebody and set an example.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Was there any kind of punishment besides the cane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you just get told off for certain things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. Just the cane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did this apply to girls and boys alike?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Mostly the boys, the girls were pretty well behaved. It was the boys that used to create all the trouble. They used to tease the girls in class and the girls would perhaps weep and tell the teacher who'd done it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did your parents show an interest in your school work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
I don't think so. Not particularly. Very proud of you id you'd one something. Just now and again there'd be a competition in school for the best essay and this might be shown at a sort of exhi
bition where the parents might come round and look at it, and you might be patted on the back for something that you'd done that was exceptional.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Your parents did come into school sometimes then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Very rarely. Didn't interfere much. Probably once
 a year when there'd be an exhibition of school work. And if you'd done something to merit being posted on the exhibition in the way of an essay or a drawing or a painting, the parents would be very pleased about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did your parents meet your teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. There was no consultation at all between parents and teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did the other children at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} school come from similar types of home to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 They were a very mixed crowd, of course. You'd have some ragamuffin types, wi
th parents who didn't care or who couldn't afford decent clothes, obviously bought their clothes at rummage sales or second hand shops or pawn shops, and came to school untidy, especially round the necks. Some of the boys would wear a scarf and a nice cle
an celluloid }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12860372\charrsid15301266 collar}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
 which could be washed every day. If you wore a collar then you came from a good home - that was a real distinguishing mark.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 The school would be a cross section of the locality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 The teachers used to single out the bright children for special scholarship tuition?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
The headmaster would when you got into the higher standard. Standard 6 was the top standard, so if there were any bright boys in standard 5, as I was, I was promoted to standard 6 before my time in order to join the scholarship class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did they single out any other groups for different treatment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Were there any favouritism or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. If you were a favourite you were a well behaved one, you see, and pointed out as an example to the rest who weren't so well behaved.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Were there any gangs among the children?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Not school gangs. The gangs were neighbourhood gangs, your own playmates in the immediate neighbourhood. We used to gang up against the Wesleyans you se
e and when snow came the thing was you'd go and snowball the Wesleyans. We used to have running fights with the neighbouring school which was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Seymour Road{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, there was a Wesleyan school there and no boys used to gang up and fight the Wesleyans with snowballs. There were no gangs in the school. In later school life you'd have your own particular friends in school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did any of the children seem to be left out of things? In the school playtimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes, the nervous types. You could pick them out. Perha
ps the ones that were badly treated at home. You could see they responded in two ways - you either became aggressive or you sunk into an inferiority complex and just didn't take part in school activities. You stood by the school wall in play times and cou
ldn't join in - these were the nervous types. And then on the other hand there were the aggressive types who came from poor homes. I suppose the psychological effect there was to become aggressive and fight and show that - well - they were somebody.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would you say that the children made any attempt to encourage the nervous ones to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. They just went there own way. They would have a poor time the nervous ones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would you have stayed on longer at school if you could have done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. I think the ambition there was to leave school and get a job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You did attend part-time classes after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would you like to tell me about some of the things you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Well my first job on leaving school was an errand boy to an Ironmonger firm in the town. And for 5/- a week I used to work from 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 8}}}8 o'clock{\*\xmlclose} in the morning 'till {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 8}}}8 o'clock{\*\xmlclose}
 at night, delivering orders from this firm. A very important firm with a shop in Deansgate and they used to supply the wealthier classe
s, the Chorley New Road classes, the west end types, with domestic requirements; and also they were builders' merchants. And my job as an errand boy was to either take parcels out up {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Chorley New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and deliver them or deliver ironmongery and builders' re
quirements to building sites with a hand truck. A builder would ring up and say he wanted so many drain pipers or down spouts, nails or screws, nuts or bolts, and I would deliver these on a hand cart, probably within any distance up to two miles from the 
town centre, with a hand cart.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How did you get this job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
I just went down and applied for it. A friend of mine in my Sunday School class had already got himself a job as an errand boy with this firm. I told him I was leaving school at Christmas 
and looking for a job and he knew I was looking for a job and he had already got a job as errand boy with this firm said "We want another errand boy, come down. If you come down you'll probably get the job." So I went down and I got this job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What hours did you work there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 From eight in the morning 'till eight at night. And 'till {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}
{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 1}}}one o'clock{\*\xmlclose} on a Saturday.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What about meal breaks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 One hour for dinner and half an hour for tea. And we used to finish at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 8}}}eight o'clock{\*\xmlclose}, then I was expected 
to go to night school, which wasn't really right because night school used to run from seven 'til nine so I only got an hour instead of two hours' tuition. And I was so tired it was no good to me because I used to fall asleep, in the heated class room, tr
y
ing to learn commercial arithmetic, and shorthand and book keeping. I went in for a commercial course, being in business then as a boy, and hoping to rise to something a bit more in the profession. I was encouraged to go to night school but I'm afraid for
 the first three years of my night school life I was much too tired to have any benefit of night school work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you sit any exams there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. Well later on. I had this errand boys job for a matter of ten months and then my father thought this w
as not quite the thing and he encouraged me to sit an exam for a job at the Co-op.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Was that when your association with the Co-op began then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Well this errand boy job with the ironmonger, this was your first full time job wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You were there for ten months - did you have any holidays during that period?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. I don't remember any.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Can you remember what you were paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 5/-.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 For what you were doing, and considering what wages were, did you feel that this was a fair wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you give any of the money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. All of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What was it spent on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 It went into the family pool.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did she give any of it back to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 2d.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Were you carrying on with your paper round at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh no. I gave that up when I left school. It was only an after school job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How did you get on with the other people at work at the ironmongers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You knew the other boy that had been at school with you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes we were the two errand boys, doing the same job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What about the other people who worked there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 They were seniors. We got on with them all right. They used to treat us fairly well. It was a shop that employed probably fourteen or 
fifteen people in and about the shop. And there were section heads you see and the great boss himself, George Grayson, who was a man to be feared. He used to come down to work at nine o'clock in the morning, after things had got going and he was the man w
ho'd call us into the office if we'd done anything reported by the section head. We'd go into the office and get ticked off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How did you feel he treated you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 I suppose fair enough but sometimes we thought he was a bit unfair you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 A bit harsh you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Yes. They were disciplinarians. "You don't do this my boy." Sometimes you'd got windows to clean and these were inspected by the boss and if they weren't clean enough to suit him you would be ticked off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How did you feel about the work itself? Did you like it or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Not particularly. We thought it was a bit rough to have to pull a truck about town. Some of it we liked. We liked to deliver parcels up 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Chorley New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} because this meant a free tram ride. We'd have half a doze
n parcels and load them on to a tram and deliver them as we went along. And we had a pass to go on the tram in the form of an arm badge, this was what we liked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 And did the tram wait for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. We would get off at the first call. We'd probably have half a dozen parcels to deliver to the better class houses. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2702408\charrsid15301266 Deliver them to the madeismen\rquote s entrance.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
 We'd deliver them and then wait for the next tram to take you further on. Because you had a badge contract and when you were on this particular duty
 you would be given an arm badge. The work was shared between the two errand boys because this was quite nice work. Free tram riding. Then the other days you would be put on the merchant sort of end. And this meant a hand }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15554005\charrsid15301266 \{ILLEGIBLE\}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266  which was pretty tough.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You then went on to the co-op. When would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Just before my fourteenth birthday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What did you have to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Deliver milk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 That was the first stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. That was the first stage of co-operative employment. To deliver
 milk on a milk round. And for that you used to report at a quarter past seven in the morning and deliver milk 'til about {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname 
Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 1}}}one o'clock{\*\xmlclose}. Then you'd come in and clean up all the cans. It was loose milk delivered in milk cans with a horse and milk float. There
 was a man in charge of the round and you was his boy and helped him to deliver milk. And about half past one or {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 45}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}
{\xmlattrvalue 1}}}quarter to two{\*\xmlclose} you'd go home for a meal and you'd come back again at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 4}}}
four o'clock{\*\xmlclose}. It was a sort of split duty because there was an evening round as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How long did you do this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Two years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What time did you work on 'til when you came back at four?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 'Til about {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 7}}}seven o'clock{\*\xmlclose} by the time you'd cleaned up after you'd delivered the milk; you used to have to wash all your cans and the kits you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Who saw to the horse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 The driver. The man in charge of the round. He had to go and feed the horse and bed it down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You were on that particular type of work for two years. What were you paid for doing that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 5/-. Then you got 1/- rise on your first birthday. At fourteen 5/- and at fifteen 6/-.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you have any holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. One week's holiday with pay.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you go on giving all the money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Were you still getting the same back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Still 2d. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How did you find the people you worked with at the Co-op?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Oh all right. There was a lot of boys. There was about then forty to fifty milk rounds, so there was 40-50 boys, so a lot of rough play about, especi
ally when you was washing up when you came in. But this was again under strict supervision. You had bosses who looked after you and inspected your work. They used to look at your kits and cans to see whether they were properly cleaned and you weren't allo
wed to go home 'til they were properly cleaned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you like this work or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
On the whole, yes. But I thought it was a bit unfair having to work Sunday mornings, because it was every morning; Sundays, Christmas Days, Bank Holidays, This was the
 time when we used to feel it a bit unjust. That we couldn't have the same holidays that other boys had. We had to turn out the whole year round, except for the week's holiday. And again I was too tired to get the full benefit out of night school. I was t
a
ught the elements of book keeping, and probably my arithmetic improved, but apart from that I didn't get the full benefit because I was too tired. And I can remember falling asleep on occasions because of being out of doors all day and going straight from
 work into a heated class room. I used to find I couldn't concentrate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How did you find the Co-op as an employer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 They were model employers. It was a great thing to get on the Co-op. It was considered quite a good safe respectable job once you go
t on the Co-op.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You went on after your two years of delivering milk into some other aspect of Co-op?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Yes. Then you were drafted into the shop life from the milk department. The biggest employer of junior labour was of course the grocery departme
nt. But before I went into the grocery department I served a term as errand boy in the gents outfitters, mostly specialising in hats, caps, collars and ties, and umbrellas. The manager of this shop wanted a boy so he reported this to the secretary of the 
C
o-op, and he would inform the dairy manager that a senior boy, (in turn, the senior boy of the milk department would go into the department that required a boy) and this happened to be in my case the gents outfitting department. And I went there as sort o
f errand boy and window cleaner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did your hours of duty change?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. Slightly better. From 8.30 in the morning, instead of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}
{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 8}}}eight o'clock{\*\xmlclose}, but there were late nights on Fridays and Saturdays. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 9}}}Nine o'clock{\*\xmlclose} on Friday and eight on Saturdays.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 And normal shop hours the other days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}
{\xmlattrvalue 8}}}Eight o'clock{\*\xmlclose} mostly. I had one what I think we called an early night. I think it was Mondays and Tuesdays, 7.30, Wednesdays early closing at one o'clock, Thursdays eight, Fridays nine, and Saturdays eight o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did those hours apply to the other departments too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. General hours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 So that those would be the hours you would be working from then up 'til the end of the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. Until I joined the army.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you have any other job with them before you joined up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
I was transferred from this job as errand boy to the grocery department, which was supposed in those days to be a sort of apprenticeship - apprenticed grocer. You went into the grocery department and there you learnt the trad
e of being a grocer. Then of course night school became some benefit, because then I joined what we called institute classes and became a qualified grocer. I went two years, first year and second year grocery classes with examinations here. Then of course
 the war came along in 1914 and this was the end of night school and a different life altogether.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 In these other departments in the Co-op, did you like the work there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Not particularly, but it was better than going in the mill or the foundry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did pay increase on transfer from one department to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. Pay increased according to age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 And then you went into the forces because of the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Could we just go back for a moment to those part-time activities that you di
d? When you were still at school there was a period when you took the spinners breakfast and then you had your paper round; was there anything else that you did as a means of earning an odd little bit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. Apart from odd pennies I got from neighbours for doing jobs - errands mostly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How did you get the paper round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Just went to the newsagent and asked to be considered for the next vacancy. They were always changing as these boys went into full time employment. There was always a demand for 
a paper boy and as long as you were clean and presented a good appearance you for the job.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What exactly did you have to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You kept a book and delivered the papers and collected the money on Saturday mornings. You kept a record in the book of 
the papers you delivered and was occupied all Saturday morning collecting the money from the people you had delivered the papers to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What time did you have to begin?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Half-past four in the evening we started, and finished at half-past six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Was this on Saturdays and Sundays too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
No. Not Sundays. Saturdays mornings, and this was up to you, if you wanted to earn extra pennies you'd go round selling football papers Saturday nights.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You would go round selling them in the streets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Yes. We used to short and people used to come and buy a football paper, if they were interested in football results. You'd run along the streets shouting "football final" and people would come up to their doors and whistle for you and you'd sell them a pa
per, and we used to get 2d for every dozen we sold. This was extra to the 2/- a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How long were you doing that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Twelve months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you have any holiday at all from that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 And again you would give the money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Yes. But she would perhaps give me an extra, allow me to put some in my money box. If I'd earned an extra 8d or 10d, or if it had been an important cup final or something like that it might amount to 1/- earned extra on Saturday night, and my mother w
ould probably give me 2d or 3d to go in my savings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How did you feel about the job? Did you like doing it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Well it was earning money, this was the point. There was an economic motive.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How did the newsagent treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Fair enough. All right. It was up to him to treat you properly or else you'd pack in the job.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would he employ other boys on the rounds as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. There was two or three of us from the same shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How did you get on with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 All right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did having a job like this alter your attitude towards school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No I don't think it made any difference to school life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 It didn't make you want to leave any sooner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 I think it gave you a sense of feeling that you were doing something to help your
 parents help the family. There was a little bit of satisfaction there which gave you a sort of communal feeling that you were doing something to repay your parents and help the family along.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Well going on then to the war. Would you like to tell me how you came to be called up and what branch you were in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
This was the thing to do. This was an adventure in life. All school life had this patriotic bias - the history we were taught, the heroes of history were the soldiers and sailors. So of course t
o join the army was a great adventure. This was daring. The first might war broke out off we went down to the local artillery barracks and asked to join the local artillery, which was the thing. I remember the gang of us eighteen year olds who went down t
o
 join the artillery the night war broke out and fortunately or unfortunately were told they'd got their full complement the sergeant told us and to come back in two or three weeks' time. And I happened to go home on the Saturday night and mother asked the
 
usual question, "Where have you been tonight?" And I told her that I had been down with so and so to join the army and this was a real shock to my mother and father, and my mother wept about this, and forbid me to do anything of the kind. And as the weeks
 
progressed I was always at my mother, there was all the boys and my play mates in the same age group, they'd had the same experience with their parents, we all sort of compared notes on the following Sunday and they'd been discouraged from joining the arm
y
 by their parents, they were too young (we were too young actually because the age of recruitment was nineteen). Eventually under continued pressure I got permission to join the army, this would be late October, and the war had been going then for two mon
t
hs. Eventually my mother gave way. Of course the air was full of bands and recruitment posters and it was all the young men's duty to join the army. The pressures were very great, and of course the call to join the army was very strong. I was eventually a
llowed to go down to the recruiting office and join the army. This was in late October and by the first week in November I was on my was to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. I remember going down with half a dozen of my friends to join the army. And we all said we wanted to join
 the same regiment. We weren't particular which one so long as we could keep together. Because I was five foot nine, fairly tall for may age I was put in the artillery, and when we came out of the recruiting office that night we all found ourselves in dif
ferent regiments, according to our particular physical abilities. And I was sent off the following day to join the artillery in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}, at least in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Gosport
{\*\xmlclose}, Hampshire. There was no time to think I just had to go home and tell mother I was off the follow
ing day, and I had to go and report to my shop manager that I couldn't start work that day as I'd joined the army. I was in a shop then that employed ten men and I was first in the shop to join, the youngest boy in the shop, and they all responded with "B
ravo" and they made a collection for me and sent me off in good style. And this was the opening of a new life to me. I'd never been out of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10122088\charrsid15301266 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 {\*\xmlclose} scarcely. To go through {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}, on a train to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, was a real adventure.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you enjoy this aspect of it then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. Very much. This was a new life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What was your response to this unaccustomed freedom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Fortunately here I began to value my home religious beliefs, because I found myself among a very rough crowd. Most of them I slept with the 
first night in a big barrack room - we were given a blanket and laid on the concrete floor of an army gymnasium in an army barracks - and the language I heard and the people who were in the army in my particular group there were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10122088\charrsid15301266 terrible}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 , I'd never experie
nced anything like it before. There was all sorts of filthy language going about. I found myself amongst people I never dreamt I should be associated with. They were a very mixed crowd of course. There were a few decent lads. Some had come out of goal and
 joined the army. But here again I think religious training counted for something. I think my home background.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Your attitude to life didn't alter as a result of your army career?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. My mother gave me a lecture on wine and women and all this sort
 of thing and it stuck fast did this, I think it did really. So army life did appeal because of the drill and the adventure of the thing - this appealed very much. I enjoyed army life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Where did you get sent to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 They had so many recruits, everyb
ody was joining the army so they had more than they could cope with. It was six weeks or so we were sleeping rough in all sorts of places where they could find to put us in. I know one was an old brewery which had been commandeered. Eventually we got post
ed to training units and I was very fortunate I got posted to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Weymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and found myself in billets. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10122088\charrsid15301266 Billeted}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266  on some very nice people in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Weymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, I was fortunate here, it was a religious home a good influence with people who really did care and made us very comfortable. There were only two of us in the billet. There was an overdraft went down to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Weymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and we were billeted down the street. I think maybe a hundred in the charge of a sargent, two in this house and two in that, right down the whole street. For two months, I was }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10122088\charrsid15301266 billeted}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
 with these very nice people and then we went into tents under canvas and I began to really enjoy being in the army. I got some training as an army }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10122088\charrsid15301266 signaller}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266  which I very much enjoyed and which appealed to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Were you in the signals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. All the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you get posted out of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Britain{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. Over to France.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Almost immediately would this be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh no. We had a long period of training in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Weymouth
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, from January 'til the end of August before I passed out as a qualified signaller. Then I was posted to a battery and went through a course of training of firing on ranges, that sort of thing, and then we went out to France.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Were you in the same place in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}France{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} most of the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Right through the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Somme{\*\xmlclose}
 yes. We were posted to the Somme district in April and spent three months preparing for the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Somme{\*\xmlclose}
 battle, laying cables all over the place. Operation posts and battery positions. Trying to destroy the enemy trenches and fortifications, for three months in preparation for the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Somme{\*\xmlclose}
 battle. Oh before that we were in training with our units in the battle line, up in the Rennes Louis district then after two or three months there we were sent down on the Somme to prepare for the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Somme{\*\xmlclose}
 battle. And we were down there right through the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Somme{\*\xmlclose} battle right up 'til Christmas 1916. Then we were moved about the whole front, Ypres, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Arras{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. I was one of the fortunate ones who came home without any disability. We'd have long periods in the firing line and then we'd com
e out for three or four weeks rest, during which you played football and had a certain amount of recreation, behind the lines. No my only experience of army hospital was when I played football after the armistice and I got knee trouble and spent a few wee
k
s in hospital with this knee. But apart from being gassed - I had a small does of gas once - yes... But otherwise I was very fortunate. More fortunate that the poor boys who got in the infantry. I think out of my Sunday School class - most of us jointed f
rom the Sunday School teenagers - 17, 18, 19 year olds - very few of them came back so when I came back I considered myself indeed very very fortunate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 How long after the armistice was it before you came out of the army?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh it wasn't very long, b
ecause I came home on leave in February 1919 and I didn't go back. Everybody then was clamouring for demobilization so I applied for mine while I was home on leave and I got it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 And then you resumed your career with the Co-op?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Going back to the co-op before 1914.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you belong to a union or association?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Yes. I was elected on to the branch committee. We had roughly about a thousand members which included the outlying districts - Westhoughton, Horwich. I got pretty active in trade union work and became a branch secretary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 When would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 In the 1920's.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 But you joined when you first went into the Co-op?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you belong when you were with the iron mongers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. It was - I don't know that it was an a
ctual condition of employment. When you joined the co-op all your work mates insisted that you should be a member of the union. It was the thing to join the union, you were more or less roped in. There was pressure on you to join. It wasn't actually a con
dition of employment then, but the pressure was there. It was the thing to join the union.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Some people say that there was in those days division between trained craftsmen and other workers. You would agree with that would you?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would you say that full time work changed your attitude to life at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Yes. Because one joined educational classes run by the Co-op. You went to night school, if you were inclined that way, and I was encouraged to join classes and first of all take a saleman
's course and then a managerial course, and eventually became a branch manager and from branch manager I became a managing secretary of a co-op of a small society. I had to leave {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose}
 of course to get a branch managers job. Applied for a job in other societies.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 You feel that your career in the co-op, it influenced you because it had this method of promotion and education and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. And idealistic purpose in the co-op which through attending classes organized by the co-operative union, book
 keeping and managerial courses, to become a co-op manager. If you got certificates in economics and commercial law, arithmetic and history and principles of co-operation and eventually you became qualified on paper for a managerial capacity, and this hel
ped you to secure a job when you applied to other societies. You answered advertisements I left Bolton to become a branch manager in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Southport{\*\xmlclose}
. From Southport I applied and got a managing secretary of a small society in the Cotswolds, in the Midlands, in a little place called Fenny Compton, with a small village society where you were a very important person.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 When you first left school and went back to work you continued living at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did going to work change your relationship at all with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
I think slightly, yes. You were allowed a little bit more latitude and freedom, although the home influence was still fairly strong until later on. Mother kept an eye on your girl friend and saw that you came in at decent time on Saturday nights.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you have a specific time for coming in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes I was expected to be home by {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 11}}}eleven o'clock{\*\xmlclose}, even after I came home from the war. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname 
Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 11}}}Eleven o'clock{\*\xmlclose} was still rather late to come home on Saturday nights. And dances was taboo actually, until dancing was allowed in Sunday School and I was permitted to go to a dance in Sunday School.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you still spend your Sundays the same way going to Sunday School and to Church?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Well yes I did. But one came home for the army with ideas abo
ut whether you had been taught the truth about things and you begin to question your religious...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 I meant when you first started working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 It was only when you came out of the army that things began to change?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. New ideas. And you used to question things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you develop an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes. Very much so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 What were your views?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 My views were against war for a start. I got myself involved with the Labour party. The socialist movement.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 This was before the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No after the war. I don't think I had any strong political views before the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Before the war you weren't specially interested in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No, except at election time, when we used to look upon them as a bit of a sport.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Did you carry on spending your spare time in the same way, after you left school when you first went to work, or did you do different things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No I was interested mostly in sport. And my bitter regret about shop life, working in shops before th
e war, my teenage regret was that I had to work Saturday afternoons and couldn't join the Sunday School cricket club, or football club. And this was one thing I regretted about shop life it did deprive me of sporting activities.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Apart from going to the evening classes, did you go out in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
No I don't think so. I had three nights a week at night school and the other nights I had a bit of homework to do and for the other spare hour I used to go into the reading room at the local Library. And read about the things that interest me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you make any new friends were you started going out to work?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No I kept to my old school friends - they boys I made friends with at school. You sorted your own particular group of friends out, and
 that was mainly on Sundays, and we'd chum up and go for walks. And take an interest in girl friends, which was frowned on at home, even when you were sixteen or seventeen. Girl friends were taboo, sex life was very taboo.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did you have any special friends at this time? And take them home sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 No. Not a great deal. The few of us would meet outside Sunday School and we'd walk the parade you know which was at 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Astley{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Yes. I had two or three very close friends which I made at day school.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 And you would continue on your Sunday evening walks with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 
Yes. No. I don't think so. Well, one of my closest friends, very closest friend, was killed in the war and that unsettled me after the war. When I came back after the war I was ver
y unsettled with my job. I went to join the police force but was rejected, I came out of the army with this injured knee and that prevented me joining the police force. I also applied for another job in the post office. I'd had some training in signaling,
 telephone work and I remember applying for a job at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Rochdale{\*\xmlclose} as a post office engineer. They were applying for ex-signal service men for {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Rochdale{\*\xmlclose}
 post office. And I remember going there and there was a queue there of about 20 ex-servicemen and I was at the end of the queue and by the time my time came they'd got all they wanted. And so I just settled down to the job of being a grocer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Previous to that would you have preferred any other occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes, I would but I hadn't the qualifications. I w
anted to be a journalist. There were two things I wanted to be - a professional footballer and a professional cricketer, or a journalist. When I left school I would have liked to have gone and been a reporter on the local paper but I hadn't a secondary sc
h
ool education and that barred me and when my brothers finished his secondary school career he went and got the job I always hankered after and he became a cub reporter on the Bolton Evening News and I used to envy him. I was really jealous about this. Bec
a
use he used to go to football matches with the senior reporter and learn his job at football and cricket matches and the local council and things like that. And I used to be very jealous and very envious. And this was when I really missed my secondary sch
ool education. If I could have chosen my career that's what it would have been. I think I would have made a very good reporter because I was interested in things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Would your parents expect to know where you were and who you were with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13773995 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Did your parents meet your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733122 FB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8596504\charrsid15301266 Oh yes. I could take them home if I wanted to, but our particular later interests were outdoors. Always outdoors never inside.
\par }}